1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,610
Throughout this lesson, we've talked about ways you can

2
00:00:02,610 --> 00:00:05,085
download and store data on your local system,

3
00:00:05,085 --> 00:00:07,950
such as by using basic Python file handling,

4
00:00:07,950 --> 00:00:12,150
pandas to CSV function, json.dumps, etc.

5
00:00:12,150 --> 00:00:14,940
But these methods and data storage don't always match up to

6
00:00:14,940 --> 00:00:19,325
industry production grade means because they are problematic for large datasets.

7
00:00:19,325 --> 00:00:22,080
Don't have clear cut standards on how the data is

8
00:00:22,080 --> 00:00:26,160
structured and can make sharing data cumbersome for large teams.

9
00:00:26,160 --> 00:00:28,770
Let's talk about a popular way of storing data through

10
00:00:28,770 --> 00:00:31,350
a much more popular option, databases.

11
00:00:31,350 --> 00:00:36,125
A database is organized collection of data that is structured to facilitate the storage,

12
00:00:36,125 --> 00:00:39,680
retrieval, modification, and deletion of data.

13
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:41,645
They have a lot of great features,

14
00:00:41,645 --> 00:00:45,020
including being very fast for accessing and writing data.

15
00:00:45,020 --> 00:00:47,840
Having administrative features like access controls and

16
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:51,940
checks to ensure data is entered in the appropriate format, etc.

17
00:00:51,940 --> 00:00:54,480
There are two main types of databases.

18
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:57,140
Relational databases, which store datasets that are

19
00:00:57,140 --> 00:01:00,445
related to each other in a structural, tabular manner.

20
00:01:00,445 --> 00:01:02,810
SQL or Structured Query Language,

21
00:01:02,810 --> 00:01:06,050
is the standard language for communicating with relational databases.

22
00:01:06,050 --> 00:01:08,525
We also have non-relational databases,

23
00:01:08,525 --> 00:01:10,370
which stores datasets that are complex,

24
00:01:10,370 --> 00:01:14,305
and cannot be captured in a tabular format like images or video.

25
00:01:14,305 --> 00:01:16,600
Take a look at an example of how

26
00:01:16,600 --> 00:01:19,795
the tabular data at the right is stored in a relational database.

27
00:01:19,795 --> 00:01:23,530
Very similar to the format we're familiar with in Microsoft Excel.

28
00:01:23,530 --> 00:01:28,100
This data is containing IDs for each of the rows in the data, and account ID,

29
00:01:28,100 --> 00:01:31,600
and occurred at column capturing the date and time of an interaction event and

30
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:35,425
the channel which contains values like direct, Twitter, etc.

31
00:01:35,425 --> 00:01:37,975
This dataset can help us answer questions like

32
00:01:37,975 --> 00:01:40,960
how many viewers access to my site in a particular time period,

33
00:01:40,960 --> 00:01:42,590
and by what channel?

34
00:01:42,590 --> 00:01:46,180
Now, let's take a look at an example of using a SQL query where I only

35
00:01:46,180 --> 00:01:49,955
want to get the rows in this dataset where the channel is Twitter.

36
00:01:49,955 --> 00:01:52,030
We can use the select clause to

37
00:01:52,030 --> 00:01:54,770
identify which elements from the database we want to pull.

38
00:01:54,770 --> 00:01:56,895
In this case, we use the asterisk

39
00:01:56,895 --> 00:02:00,235
indicating all of them meeting the following conditions.

40
00:02:00,235 --> 00:02:02,955
Next, we specify from.

41
00:02:02,955 --> 00:02:05,825
Here we want to pull data from a table called web events,

42
00:02:05,825 --> 00:02:07,760
which is the table depicted on the right.

43
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:13,165
Next, we specify where to filter our results to indicate the channel as Twitter.

44
00:02:13,165 --> 00:02:15,740
Now, take a look at the results on the screen where we see

45
00:02:15,740 --> 00:02:19,820
the filter results showing all the rows where the channel is Twitter.

46
00:02:19,820 --> 00:02:22,340
In the context of data wrangling, databases,

47
00:02:22,340 --> 00:02:26,280
and SQL come into play typically when gathering data, or storing data.

48
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:29,660
That is connecting to a database and importing data into

49
00:02:29,660 --> 00:02:31,010
a pandas DataFrame or

50
00:02:31,010 --> 00:02:34,055
the analagous data structure in your preferred programming language.

51
00:02:34,055 --> 00:02:39,440
Or storing data onto a database after you gather the data or clean the data.

52
00:02:39,440 --> 00:02:43,805
These tasks are especially necessary when you have large amounts of data,

53
00:02:43,805 --> 00:02:48,450
which is where SQL and other databases Excel over flat files.

